                type="document" xml:id="d9">
                <head>9. Editorial Note</head>
                <p>On January 28, 1964, a Soviet fighter shot down a U.S. T–39 training aircraft
                    over East Germany. The three U.S. officers aboard were killed. At noon on
                    January 28 Secretary of Defense <persName corresp="#p_MNRS1">McNamara</persName>
                    telephoned President <persName corresp="#p_JLB1">Johnson</persName> to brief him
                    on the incident. <persName corresp="#p_MNRS1">McNamara</persName> told <persName
                        corresp="#p_JLB1">Johnson</persName> the flight had been cleared “only for
                    local flying,” but, probably due to bad weather and failure of its communication
                    equipment, it had strayed into East German airspace. <persName
                        corresp="#p_MNRS1">McNamara</persName> assured the President that the
                    aircraft was not on an intelligence mission. (Johnson Library, Recordings and
                    Transcripts, Recording of a Telephone Conversation, Tape F64.08, Side A, PNO 6)
                    The Soviet note protesting the intrusion, January 29, and the U.S. oral reply,
                    made to Soviet Deputy Chief of Mission <persName corresp="#p_KGM1"
                        >Kornienko</persName> the same day, are printed in <hi rend="italic"
                        >American Foreign Policy: Current Documents</hi>, 1964, pages 526–527. In
                    its reply, the United States called the Soviet action an “inexcusably brutal act
                    of violence against an unarmed aircraft.”</p>
